{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 07:04:10.165710", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Network troubleshooting diagnosis report\n\nScope\n- Detect anomalies\n- Localize faulty devices\n- Identify likely root cause\n- No remediation proposed\n\nHigh-level assessment\n- IP connectivity across the enterprise appears healthy: broad end-to-end reachability with 0% loss and low RTTs (typ. 2–5 ms) between representative subnets.\n- OSPF routing is converged and consistent: 10.200.0.0/24 (server farm) is advertised and reachable; the backend network 20.200.0.0/24 is intentionally not in the OSPF domain (as designed).\n- DHCP and DNS services appear functional: hosts have valid addressing and resolve service names correctly to expected IPs.\n- Web application layer shows anomalies: public web servers are not running Apache as specified; both public and backend servers return 501 to HEAD requests (indicating BaseHTTP/0.6 Python server behavior), and measured HTTP totals are ~1.0–1.2 s despite low RTTs, suggesting application-layer delay rather than network impairment.\n\nDetailed findings\n\nRouting and reachability\n- Host reachability: Extensive ICMP tests across multiple access subnets show 0% loss and low RTTs.\n- OSPF routes:\n  - Core and distribution routers have consistent OSPF entries for all 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 access subnets and for 10.200.0.0/24 via server_access_router.\n  - server_access_router has 10.200.0.0/24 directly connected and full reachability to all access subnets via 172.16.0.22/31.\n  - 20.200.0.0/24 is not present in any core/dist/server router tables (confirmed with “show ip route 20.200.0.0/24” on core_1 returning “% Network not in table”), matching the design that backend web servers should not be reachable from hosts.\n- Load balancer network: load_balancer has eth0 on 10.200.0.7/24 and eth1 on 20.200.0.1/24, with default route via 10.200.0.1. It can ping 20.200.0.2/3/4 successfully (0% loss, <1 ms).\n\nDNS\n- Host resolvers: /etc/resolv.conf on hosts point